<TEXT>
president reagan called it a little homework 
assignment 
prepare a report he told his education secretary william j 
bennett assessing the progress of school reform five years after a 
national commission warned in its landmark study a nation at 
risk of a rising tide of mediocrity 
the resulting 60page report american education making it 
work issued last week at a white house ceremony turned out to 
be more than bennetts notsofond look at what schools have and 
have not accomplished since reform began in earnest in 1983 
try as it might to appear otherwise and its not clear that it 
tried all that hard this little homework assignment is now 
being read for its political as well as educational content coming 
as it does in the midst of the presidential primary season 
the barbs start immediately in the introduction signed by 
bennett 
schools are slightly improved from 1983 said bennett but 
we are still at risk the absolute level at which our 
improvements are taking place is unacceptably low a conclusion 
few quarreled with last week 
however in explaining why reform has not progressed quickly 
the education secretary took aim at those practicing what he called 
opposition by extortion the false claim that to fix our schools 
will first require a fortune in new funding 
he said that narrow selfinterested parties are too often 
succeeding in blocking changes by legislatures and school boards 
teacher unions blocked reform by going to court in 
louisiana under teacher union pressure texas eliminated key 
sections of that states teacher competency test alabama facing 
opposition from administrators and the teacher union abandoned 
its career ladder program 
now who exactly might bennett have been talking about 
hint the national education association was one of the only 
major education groups not invited to the white house ceremony last 
week nea activists instead protested at a nearby park 
the oblique way bennett repeated his old charge that special 
interests and we all know which party they dominate and a 
certain teacher union in particular are big spenders and 
halfhearted reformers sounded a bit like the old archie bunker 
quip i aint mentioning names i just look at the party and 
whistle 
the bennett report then could wind up sharpening the battle 
lines between rival approaches to education reform in this 
political year 
to the extent that it foreshadows its partys platform on 
education the reagan administration is saying here that we could 
have had better schools by now we know how to do it we know what 
works the answer is not more money and new federal programs the 
problem is lack of political willpower and guts to face down the 
special interests who slow reform because it threatens their 
stranglehold on schools 
teacher unions and others in the educational community replied 
last week that the republican position as stated in the bennett 
report is just further proof that the reagan administration offered 
years of talk but not much action and certainly not much federal 
support for school reform 
its conceivable that the democrats will echo those sentiments 
in their platform 
in his weekly paid column scheduled for publication in sundays 
new york times american federation of teachers president albert 
shanker wrote an open letter to bennett bitterly criticizing 
his report especially on the money issue 
of course better schools arent only a matter of money said 
shanker but you lose credibility every time you repeat that 
statement after all families that have more money do move to and 
live in districts that spend more on their schools they seem to 
know that money does make a difference 
and he voiced frustration over bennetts constant barbs at 
teachers and others in the education field 
instead of leading your troops you kept shooting at them as 
though all who disagreed with you were misguided shanker said 
the bennett report was silent on the federal role in education 
a fact criticized last week not just by teacher unions and school 
interest groups but by among others university of california 
president david gardner who chaired the national commission that 
produced a nation at risk 
given the political bent of this latest report practically no 
one was expressing the belief last week that it would have the 
spectacular impact that a nation at risk had five years ago in 
rallying support for and defining the direction of school reform 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
lee mitgang has covered education for the 
associated press since 1981 
</TEXT>
