<TEXT>
barbed wire and watchtowers ring this 
communal farm on the lebanese border to fend off attacks by arab 
guerrillas but the heavy security cant keep out the fear 
the tension is growing resident yossi tal said after two 
separate raids last week by palestinian guerrillas on 
hostagetaking missions 
but tal and other kibbutzniks say decades of syrian shelling 
rocket attacks from lebanon and guerrilla raids have deepened their 
resolve to stay put 
i feel that because of what i went through in my childhood 
im more connected to this place said the 38yearold tal 
speaking in his sunlit garden apartment as he hugged his 1yearold 
daughter 
added his wife esti 38 when it gets too difficult i 
sometimes think about leaving but its important that we live 
here because we must show that we cant be run out of our 
country 
in the past five months however her commitment was sorely 
tested as arab guerrillas stepped up border raids to keep up 
momentum of a palestinian uprising in the israelioccupied west 
bank and gaza strip 
the latest infiltrations may also stem in part from the 
assassination of khalil wazir the military commander of the 
palestine liberation organization who was gunned down april 16 at 
his home in tunisia 
kibbutz dan is in israels northeastern tip one of the most 
vulnerable areas along the border infiltrators passing through 
south lebanon to reach the border encounter few hostile lebanese 
militias and the rocky mountain terrain provides good cover 
in separate raids tuesday and wednesday palestinian guerrilla 
squads with automatic rifles hand grenades and maps of border 
settlements sneaked past israeli patrols and descended the steep 
slopes of mount dov two miles east of dan 
in tuesdays predawn infiltration three guerrillas hiding in a 
thicket of bushes on the mountain killed two israeli soldiers 
before troops gunned them down 
on wednesday two guerrillas ambushed an israeli truck driving 
up mount dov and wounded the driver they fled and hundreds of 
foot patrols backed by helicopter gunships searched for more than 
three hours before spotting them in a ravine and killing them 
in both cases dan and its 550 residents went on red alert 
tiger three tiger three shouted a voice over the kibbutz 
loudspeakers telling residents through the codeword that 
guerrillas were nearby 
we were in the dining hall eating lunch when the word came 
said robert andersson 21 a volunteer from the swedish island of 
orust everybody was running out 
the men grabbed submachine guns and dashed to assigned guard 
posts and watchtowers along the barbed wire fence while others 
circled the kibbutz in jeeps the women stayed indoors with 
children 
we went to our rooms and locked the doors said hagit bal 
15 we heard very heavy shooting a lot of helicopters 
hagit a softspoken teenager with a blond ponytail said she 
hates the guerrillas because they hate us and want to kill us 
when i was little i used to have nightmares that they would 
come and shoot us she said the figures in her dreams were 
dark and ugly with a moustache 
tals teenage son yoni who was born during the 1973 golan 
heights war said he used to spend weeks at a time in underground 
shelters while guerrillas from lebanon bombarded the northern 
israeli settlements with sovietmade katyusha rockets 
our nurses would tell us our fathers were fighting for us but 
i was afraid something would happen to them said yoni a new 
wave music fan sporting a rats tail hair cut 
i know that my children have to suffer this tension said 
tal who was born in dan and my grandchildren probably will go 
through the same thing and also my greatgrandchildren 
he recalled that before the 1967 middle east war the syrian 
border was only 500 yards from dan and trenches five feet deep 
crisscrossed the kibbutz as a protection against syrian shelling 
i remember one day in 1964 when they fired more than 300 
shells in two hours said tal nobody was hurt but the place 
was devastated 
a day after wednesdays guerrilla infiltration life was back to 
normal in dan farmers donned gray and blue work uniforms and 
returned to their apple orchards trout ponds and honey bee hives 
children rode bicycles along treelined paths linking neatly kept 
white garden apartments 
meir dayan 21 who stood near the communal dining hall with an 
uzi submachine gun resting on his shoulder said kibbutzniks have 
learned to quickly pick up their routine after each alert 
this he said is our way of life 
</TEXT>
