<TEXT>
welfare checks for about 400 wisconsin 
families will be cut this month in the first phase of a program 
that uses benefit reductions as a means of forcing dropouts back to 
school 
the learnfare program passed by the legislature last year 
requires reductions in aid to families with dependent children 
benefits for welfare families where teenagers fail to attend 
school regularly 
the program entered its first phase in march when penalties 
were assessed against welfare recipients ages 13 and 14 and to teen 
parents on welfare who failed to meet the schooling requirements 
but those penalties didnt start showing up on welfare checks until 
this month 
the penalties applied if a teenage parent on welfare or welfare 
children 13 and 14 years old dropped out of school or were absent 
more than two days a month without a valid reason 
the program will apply to 15 to 17yearolds in september 
in a recent report to the legislature health and social 
services secretary timothy cullen said only 395 of 16289 afdc 
families affected by the first phase of the program will be 
penalized a breakdown showed 309 cases involved teen parents and 
86 cases involved afdc families 
were pleased that the numbers are this low cullen said 
we know the numbers of dropouts are several hundred lower than 
if there hadnt been a learnfare program 
cullen said there was no way to determine how many welfare 
teenagers had been going to school before learnfare 
although cullen said the program will help students stay off 
welfare when theyre adults one critic said it will do little good 
failure thats what schools should be addressing their 
failure and the kids failure said state rep rebecca young a 
former city school board member we shouldnt be forcing kids 
back to school simply so theres another body there 
benefits will be cut an average 100 a month for each month the 
students remain out of school or miss more than two days 
the state bureau of economic assistance said the average afdc 
benefit check is 517 per month but that the cut would make 
beneficiaries eligible for an extra 33 in food stamps 
the program has no effect on medical assistance to welfare 
families 
cullen also noted that recipients may appeal for exemption from 
learnfare in cases where school officials determine that teenagers 
are so far behind in schoolwork they will not be able to graduate 
by age 19 
some may also appeal benefit penalties if they can show there 
was inadequate day care and transportation services to help them 
attend school cullen said 
a number of those cases exemptions will involve teen 
parents cases where the person dropped out at age 14 and is 17 now 
and could not possibly graduate by 19 he said 
young said learnfare unfairly penalizes welfare recipients while 
ignoring dropouts and truants from more affluent families 
if were going to do this we should extend it to all and 
penalize them nonwelfare families a fifth of their monthly gross 
income young said 
young also said the program puts too much pressure on families 
already hurt by emotional conflicts and does not give schools the 
educational tools they need handle unruly teenagers or students 
who believe they are failures 
if a kid fails in school this is not the best way to enforce 
good behavior we should find out what made them fail in the first 
place young said 
cullen said however that many school districts have upgraded 
attendance policies procedures to notify parents of absences and 
programs to help children who are at risk of educational failure 
