the new york city ballet entered the second week 
of its threeweek american music festival on sunday with the odd 
nightmarish archetypes with ballerinas in clown masks and men 
dressed as admirals 
in part 1 the ballerinas in masks take heather watts from her 
partner jock soto and when he sees her again she has become like 
all of them he runs in part 2 men in threepiece suits with 
briefcases are vaguely menaced by men in leotards and ski masks 
part 3 starts amusingly as miss watts black coat is whisked 
into the air leaving her in underwear she dances a long sensual 
duet with soto in admirals uniform and gray hair he tosses away 
his elderly wig but instead of a happy ending other admirals carry 
him away and her coat flies back and she leaves part 4 started 
fast and passionate and ended with what looked like a gang fight 
dancers looked as though they needed more rehearsal 
paul schwartz composed the music on commission from the new york 
city ballet choreographer robert weiss formerly of the new york 
city ballet wrote a program note saying his ballet was inspired by 
paintings by jonathan borofsky 
the second ballet of the evening was jerome robbins wonderful 
amusing fancy free to music by leonard bernstein from 1944 
the evening in the new york state theater ended with lars 
lubovitchs rhapsody in blue to the famous gershwin music 
which was danced on the festivals opening night 
the principal male part looks as though it was choreographed for 
rangy christopher damboise who isnt with the company any more 
the movement is the kind of free widekicking fastspinning 
highlifting dancing that says america from cheerleaders to 
barndancers its the energetic movement of a big country 
