<TEXT>
a conscientious objector who had been 
given his last rites called off a 68day hunger strike sunday after 
the government pledged to reform the law on military service his 
support committee said 
michalis marangakis 31yearold wood carver from the northern 
city of salonica started the hunger strike february 22 while 
serving a 26month sentence for refusing to serve in the army 
marangakis said he wouldnt eat until the government established 
an alternative option to mandatory military service such as social 
work 
last month he was transferred from a military jail to the athens 
401 military hospital after losing 61 pounds his weight dropped 
from 198 pounds to 136 pounds during the hunger strike 
on saturday marangakis was reported in critical condition and 
received the last rites from a greek orthodox priest theodoros 
michalopoulos a member of the greek committee for conscientious 
objectors told the associated press by telephone 
he said defense undersecretary stathis yiotas visited marangakis 
in hospital on sunday and gave him a written assurance the law 
would be altered 
a government statement issued sunday said only that legislation 
on military service for conscientious objectors will be reviewed 
a law passed by parliament in february and due to take effect in 
september will permit conscientious objectors to serve four years 
in the armed services as noncombatants instead of the regular 
twoyear stint 
but the law makes no provision for alternative service by 
conscientious objectors who refuse to join the armed forces 
